@Node "> Starting the Server (pronet-server)" "ProNET.guide/> Starting the Server (pronet-server)"
@Toc "Main"

Starting the Server (@{b}pronet-server@{ub})
===================================

   For any Amiga you want to use as a server, you first have to start
@{b}pronet-server@{ub}. By default, this program waits for incoming request
on `ProNET' Unit 0, but you can change this by supplying another value
in the command line, so, if you had several connections to a central
server computer, you would have to start @{b}pronet-server@{ub} once for every
Unit.

   If you forget to start the server, client programs will simply go
into an endless loop, so when later on nothing seems to work, always
check if the server is running!

   The server can be stopped at any time by issueing a @{b}CTRL-C@{ub} signal.
I would do so before rebooting the Client machine, since the server will
then give notice of its departure.  I suggest starting the server with
@{b}run <>nil:@{ub} so it doesn't block your shell.  If you want to stop it,
use the @{b}status@{ub} and @{b}break@{ub} commands.


@EndNode

@Node "> Importing Devices (pronet-start)" "ProNET.guide/> Importing Devices (pronet-start)"
@Toc "Main"

Importing Devices (@{b}pronet-start@{ub})
================================

   Starting the network is a very simple job, which is done by the
@{b}pronet-start@{ub} utility.

   The command template is as follows:

     pronet-start LOCALNAME/A,REMOTENAME/A,UNIT/N,FLAGS/N,UNIQUE/S

   @{i}LOCALNAME@{ui} is the name of the Device to create while @{i}REMOTENAME@{ui} is
the one you want to import from a remote Amiga. It is important not to
give a volume name (e.g. `Work') here but the device name (such as
`hd0')!  Please also note that you must not append a `:' to the Device
names!

   As for the example from above, we could issue the command
          pronet-start cd1 cd0
                       ^^^
                       This is what we want to
                       call the device on the A4000.
                           ^^^
                           This is what the device is
                           called on the CDTV.

   The rest of the arguments don't necessarily have to be specified:

   @{i}UNIT@{ui} is the `ProNET' unit you want to use (default 0). @{i}FLAGS@{ui}
currently has no effect (defaults to 0, too) and the @{i}UNIQUE@{ui} switch makes
Volume names unique. Imagine the following configuration:

   Two Amigas with both a `Workbench' partition are connected and Amiga
1 wants to access the Workbench partition of Amiga 2. You call
@{b}pronet-start@{ub} and what happens? Now you have got two `Workbench'
volume icons on your screen.  This will confuse AmigaDOS quite heavily,
which is to be avoided by using the @{i}UNIQUE@{ui} switch. This will simply
append a number to the imported volume name, corresponding to the
`ProNET' unit you have used.

   @{b}pronet-start@{ub} returns an error message if something went wrong, that
is e.g.  when the remote device doesn't exist or the `ProNET' unit
can't be found.  Otherwise it immediately returns without further
output.  Don't start it with @{b}run@{ub}, the command immediately returns!

   Now repeat this step for every new device. Good luck!


@EndNode

@Node "> pronet-stop" "ProNET.guide/> pronet-stop"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}pronet-stop@{ub}
===========

   When you feel that you don't need a remote device any more, you can
remove it with this command. Supply @{b}pronet-stop@{ub} with the device name
you want to remove and it will do its job. You could also give the @{i}UNIT@{ui}
keyword together with a Unit number. @{b}pronet-stop@{ub} will then stop all
devices on this specific Unit.

   Why should you do this?  Well, if you switched off the Server or
reset it without stopping the Client, strange things might happen on
the Client: You couldn't access any data any more, perhaps you couldn't
even move your mouse - this is because the Client thinks the Server's
still alive!

   Beyond question: If you're going to switch off both computers
anyway, you can skip this of course.


@EndNode

@Node "> pronet-flush" "ProNET.guide/> pronet-flush"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}pronet-flush@{ub}
============

   You can use this command without further arguments to remove
@{b}pronet.device@{ub} from memory.  This will free all resources allocated
by the `ProNET' drivers.  @{b}pronet-server@{ub} and @{b}pronet-stop@{ub} have this
feature built-in.  You will hardly find appropriate use for this
command, but it's there for reasons of completeness anyway.


@EndNode

@Node "> pronet-page" "ProNET.guide/> pronet-page"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}pronet-page@{ub}
===========

   Using this program, you can send messages to users on remote
machines.  This works by calling @{b}pronet-page@{ub} with the `ProNET' Unit and
the message to be displayed on the machine connected to that Unit.

   Example:

     pronet-page 0 Hello there!

   The message will be displayed in a Guru-like alert window at the top
of the screen.


@EndNode

@Node "> pronet-run" "ProNET.guide/> pronet-run"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}pronet-run@{ub}
==========

   By using this program, you can run programs on a networked machine
without having to touch its keyboard or mouse. Call it with the
`ProNET' Unit and the command to be run on the corresponding Amiga. The
command string @{i}must@{ui} be put in @{b}"@{ub}s.

   Example:

     pronet-run 0 "dir hd0: all"
     pronet-run 13 "list >con:0/0/640/200/test"

   It is important to know that the standard output is done into the
window that the respective pronet-server was started from.  Therefore I
strongly advise you to explicitly redirect standard output, like I did
in the second example.


@EndNode

@Node "> pronet-talk" "ProNET.guide/> pronet-talk"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}pronet-talk@{ub}
===========

   This program can be used to chat between two machines. All you need
to do is call @{b}pronet-talk@{ub} on @{i}both@{ui} machines with the right `ProNET' Unit
as an argument. By default, this program uses Unit 0.


@EndNode

@Node "Advanced Usage" "ProNET.guide/Advanced Usage"
@Toc "Main"

Advanced Usage
**************

   In this chapter, I want to give you some hints to how to use the
full power of ProNET.  There are some things which are not very obvious
and may be useful for some of you.


 @{" > Reconnection            " Link "> Reconnection"}  
 @{" > Networking in both directions " Link "> Networking in both directions"}  
 @{" > A network over the phone line " Link "> A network over the phone line"} 


@EndNode

@Node "> Reconnection" "ProNET.guide/> Reconnection"
@Toc "Main"

Reconnection
============

   Okay, this is not quite what I would call advanced usage, but it's
the right place for this anyway.

   Let's get back to the example from the `Importing Devices' section.
You will sometimes have to reboot your A4000, because some program has
crashed (uuh not really, we use an Amiga ;-)).  When you want to start
the network again, you don't have to reboot the CDTV, too - It's
completely okay to issue new @{b}pronet-start@{ub} commands after a Client reboot
without rebooting the Server.  That's all.


@EndNode

@Node "> Networking in both directions" "ProNET.guide/> Networking in both directions"
@Toc "Main"

Networking in both directions
=============================

   Most configurations will look similar to the one described above,
i.e.  one main machine, the working place, and a server which is no
working place.  However, if you are networking with a friend's system
and you are both working on the machines, it's no problem to install
the network in both directions, that is both machines are Server and
Client at the same time.  The two can each access the other one's file
systems.


@EndNode

@Node "> A network over the phone line" "ProNET.guide/> A network over the phone line"
@Toc "Main"

A network over the phone line
=============================

   Imagine you have a friend living far away from you, and you want to
help him install some new programs.  You could call him and describe
exactly what he has to do, but this way you will spend far too much
time, because he will not understand (This presumption has been derived
from Murphy's Law and proved to be fact in many situations @{i};-)@{ui}).

   You could also make a modem connection, install a network between
your computers and copy all the files to the right places, make some
shell scripts etc.  on your own. Does this sound interesting?  Then
read on!

Preparation
-----------

   Both sides must define a ProNET Unit using the @{b}serial@{ub} driver.  The
respective port will not have a null-modem cable connected to it, but a
real modem!  As usual, set the serial port speed to four times the
modem speed, if your port does it.  The speed settings on both sides
don't have to be equal, because the modem manages the transfer speed on
its own.

   Both modems must be configured to ignore the DTR (data terminal
ready) signal, which is in most cases done by issueing the command
@{b}AT&D0@{ub}.

How to connect
--------------

   Load your favourite terminal programs now.  Decide one of you to be
the caller, who then dials the other one's number via @{b}ATD@{ub}.  As soon as
he has answered with @{b}ATA@{ub} and you've read the @{b}CONNECT@{ub} message, both
sides quit the terminal.

   Now simply proceed as if you were connected with a simple null-modem
cable: Start the server programs and install the devices (of course
directed to the right unit!).  That's it.  Not very fast, but nice
anyway @{i};-)@{ui}


@EndNode

